64","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1015":"1015","1179":"1179","1079":"1079","September 1064":"september 1064","about 1079":"omkring 1079","Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Orne, Normandie, Frankrig","Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Frankrig","Maine, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Charente, Poitou-Charentes, Frankrig","Lucé, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Lucé, Orne, Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1040–about 1079":"1040–circa 1079","1040–1079":"1040–1079","1030–1085":"1030–1085","1064–1179":"1064–1179","1015–1060":"1015–1060","1018–1072":"1018–1072","about 1060":"circa 1060","1064":"1064","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1015":"1015","1179":"1179","1079":"1079","September 1064":"september 1064","about 1079":"circa 1079","Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk","Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Maine, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Charente, Poitou-Charentes, Frankrijk","Lucé, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Lucé, Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1040–about 1079":"1040–about 1079","1040–1079":"1040–1079","1030–1085":"1030–1085","1064–1179":"1064–1179","1015–1060":"1015–1060","1018–1072":"1018–1072","about 1060":"about 1060","1064":"1064","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1015":"1015","1179":"1179","1079":"1079","September 1064":"September 1064","about 1079":"about 1079","Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France","Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lucé, Orne, Lower Normandy, France","Maine, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France","Lucé, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Lucé, Orne, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Lucey  .","French: habitational name from any of various places called Lucy, originally named with the Latin personal name <i>Lucius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Lucy II was born in 1040, in Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France, his father, Geoffrey de Lucy, was 25 and his mother, Rohese FitzRichard, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Roesia de Lucy. He died about 1079, in Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1040–about 1079":"1040–umbes 1079","1040–1079":"1040–1079","1030–1085":"1030–1085","1064–1179":"1064–1179","1015–1060":"1015–1060","1018–1072":"1018–1072","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1064":"1064","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","1060":"1060","1018":"1018","1015":"1015","1179":"1179","1079":"1079","September 1064":"september 1064","about 1079":"umbes 1079","Domfront, Orne, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Orne, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lucé, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Maine, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Charente, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Lucé, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Lucé, Orne, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1040–about 1079":"1040–noin 1079","1040–1079":"1040–1079","1030–1085":"1030–1085","1064–1179":"1064–1179","1015–1060":"1015–1060","1018–1072":"10